^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That wasn't so bad now, was it Lisa :). A bit on the bidding first, and then we will get to the play. Many people recommend you always bypass your diamonds to bid a major, and that is one way to play it. However, I use a somewhat different rule. If my hand is not good enough for two bids, then I would have bid 1H rather than 1D. For example, take away the Ace of clubs ( now I had 8 HCP), then I would have bid 1H not 1D.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|however, with enough points for a 2nd bid, I bid 1D and let the auction develop naturally. In this case I had 12 points, so knew we were going to game. had Lisa bid 1S over 1D, I would just bid 3N. And if she bids 1H I bid 4H. That is my rule. only bypass 1D if you don't have enough points to make a 2nd bid.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, as to the play. Kia made a defensive mistake there, otherwise the hand is down. He forgot to play 2nd hand low on the first heart. Honestly and truly, play 2nd hand low all the time, and you will be better off. For every trick you give up, you will gain two, I promise. |
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Anyway, lets look at Lisa's plan. This is a hard hand to play. On the spade lead she can count two spades, 3 hearts if hearts are 3-2, even if she loses 2 hearts, one diamond and two clubs for a total of eight tricks. So, she needs 2 more tricks. She can perhaps get an extra ruff somewhere for nine and perhaps the Q of diamonds for tenth trick. I am not sure NT is better.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, at trick 2, I would play a low diamond. If that works, then Lisa can pitch a club on the Ace of diamonds, and get rid of her club loser. She can end up ruffing 2 spades in dummy maybe and make 10 tricks that way. When that loses (such as in this case), she has to hope to pick up the hearts with only one loser. It turns out, she cannot do that against proper defense, but it is her best shot.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT|^B@2
analisals: A diamond wasn't so how do I pitch a club until I play the D Ace?  |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On this hand you cannot. But, if kia had the K of diamonds, when you lead a diamond, say he goes up with the K then leads a spade. Then you win the ace of spades, cash the Q of diamonds, ruff a spade, and pitch a club on the ace of diamonds. |
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Further, you should wait to pull trumps, try diamonds first. But as I said, this was a hard hand. With proper defense, I would have gone down myself.|
